PPP is a collaboration between government and private sector to deliver public infrastructure and services.

It involves shared risks and resources, enabling faster project completion and innovation.

India's infrastructure needs huge investment (â‚¹115 lakh crore by 2030) with funding gaps bridged by PPPs.

Key government supports include Viability Gap Funding (VGF) and dedicated PPP cells.

Common PPP models: Build-Operate-Transfer (BOT), Build-Own-Operate-Transfer (BOOT), Hybrid Annuity Model (HAM).

Successful projects like Hyderabad Metro show effectiveness of PPPs.

Challenges include land acquisition, regulatory delays, financial issues.

Focus sectors: transport, energy, ports, logistics, social infrastructure, water, sanitation.

Government promotes transparency, regulatory reforms, and capacity building for PPP success.

PPPs help bridge infrastructure gaps, improve service quality, and drive inclusive growth. 
